href="jms-00KI.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00KI">injective</fr:link>, as <fr:tex>a_0=a_1</fr:tex> implies <fr:tex>a_0=a_1</fr:tex>.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>Let <fr:tex>f \colon  A \rightarrowtail  B</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>g \colon  B \rightarrowtail  C</fr:tex> be <fr:link
href="jms-00M0.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00M0">injections</fr:link>. To show that the <fr:link
href="jms-00KI.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00KI">composite function</fr:link> <fr:tex>g \circ  f \colon  A \to  C</fr:tex> is <fr:link
href="jms-00MO.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00MO">injective</fr:link>, we fix <fr:tex>a_0,a_1 \in  A</fr:tex> to check that <fr:tex>g { \mathopen {} \left ( f { \mathopen {} \left ( a_0 \right ) \mathclose {}} \right ) \mathclose {}}  = g { \mathopen {} \left ( f { \mathopen {} \left ( a_1 \right ) \mathclose {}} \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex> implies <fr:tex>a_0=a_1</fr:tex>. Because <fr:tex>g</fr:tex> is <fr:link
href="jms-00MO.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00MO">injective</fr:link>, we have <fr:tex>f { \mathopen {} \left ( a_0 \right ) \mathclose {}} =f { \mathopen {} \left ( a_1 \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>; therefore, because <fr:tex>f</fr:tex> is <fr:link
href="jms-00MO.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00MO">injective</fr:link>, we have <fr:tex>a_0=a_1</fr:tex> as desired.</fr:p>
